b47ae429a9dbc51e237d33e83bfdc93e.description: E-mail Ruling Providing Notice of Ex Parte Communication and Requiring Response from Southern California Edison Company. On November 16, 2020 at 1:42 pm, Administrative Law Judge Kao and former Executive Director Alice Stebbins received a non-procedural e-mail from Bradley Bratz. This e-mail ruling requires Mr. Bratz to file a Notice of Ex Parte Communication no later than December 21, 2020 of the said written/email communication. This email ruling also directs Southern California Edison Company (SCE) to file a document that described every action SCE has taken since October 30, 2019 to (1) resolve and (2) notify affected customers of any delays or other issues in providing correct billing to customers receiving service under a net energy metering (NEM) tariff. This document shall also provide SCE’s best estimate of when it will resolve any NEM billing delays or associated issues. SCE shall file this document no later than December 28, 2020.

6f6c64c152734e47e0a6ccf6a23b089a.description: SUMMARY:  On February 5, 2019, Scott Crider, Vice President – Customer Affairs, and Dan Skopec, Vice President – Regulatory Affairs, of San Diego Gas & Electric Company (SDG&E), met with Sarah Sharpe and Amy Reardon, advisors to Cmmr. Guzman Aceves, in San Francisco. SDG&E discussed the structure of the SOMAH program and the challenges that SDG&E faces in implementing the program given its limited administration budget, which is not sufficient to fund needed upgrades to SDG&E’s billing system. SDG&E representatives stated that SDG&E filed an Advice Letter to complete the necessary IT work that will accommodate the complicated billing necessary for this program. SDG&E explained that the high cost of the IT work is because SDG&E’s billing system is more than 20 years old and implementing initiatives like SOMAH requires extensive work. SDG&E is replacing its billing system in 2021, which will allow programs like SOMAH to be launched faster and for significantly less money.

Guzman Aceves, in San Francisco. The solar parties discussed the timeline for the beginning of the net metering revisit, which is currently scheduled to occur in 2019, as well as the evaluation study of the current successor tariff that was ordered by Decision 18-09-044. With respect to the latter, the solar parties discussed whether the study should exclude a cost benefit analysis of the current tariff so that parties can provide their own cost benefit assessments. In addition, the solar parties addressed the use of an updated version of the DER avoided cost model as the vehicle for assessing costs and benefits in the upcoming proceeding.

a79034f3534b2b25a7fe2e16a76d9e83.filed_by: City of Lancaster,Marin Clean Energy,Peninsula Clean Energy Authority,Sonoma Clean Power Authority
a79034f3534b2b25a7fe2e16a76d9e83.description: [JOINT] SUMMARY:  On June 14, 2018, Scott Blaising, regulatory counsel for the City of Lancaster (Lancaster), Marin Clean Energy (MCE), Peninsula Clean Energy Authority (PCE), and Sonoma Clean Power Authority (SCP) (collectively, CCA Parties), met with David Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Guzman Aceves, in San Francisco. Also present was Jeremy Waen, Senior Regulatory Analyst for PCE; and Jan Pepper, Chief Executive Officer, and Jeremy Waen, Senior Regulatory Analyst, for PCE, Nathaniel Malcolm, counsel for MCE, and David Peffer, regulatory counsel for the Lancaster, participated in the meeting via teleconference. The CCA Parties’ representatives discussed matters related to Commissioner Guzman Aceves’ Alternate Revised Proposed Decision (Revised APD). The CCA Parties representatives stated their support for the programs established by Revised APD, but registered their concern that the Revised APD’s discussion of the Community Solar Green Tariff program does not sufficiently address the role and eligibility of Community Choice Aggregation (CCA) programs. The CCA Parties stated that CCA programs should qualify for funding by administering their own Community Solar Green Tariff programs. The CCA Parties pointed to Demand Response as a helpful analog for how CCA programs could participate in Community Solar Green Tariff programs. The CCA Parties asked that the Revised APD be clarified to invite CCA programs to bring forth Community Solar Green Tariff proposals on an equal footing with the investor-owned utilities (IOUs). The CCA Parties suggested that a workshop might be helpful to develop the expected framework for content in the advice letters. Regarding the Disadvantaged Communities Green Tariff program, the CCA Parties noted that in order to implement a program that is equivalent to the IOUs’ programs CCA customers must be able to offer a discount of 20% off a participating customer’s total bill, which includes both the CCA-produced generation charge and the IOU-produced delivery charge.

8c2aa0fcc7988c6cddcf0f0ac132aff5.description: SUMMARY:  On April 9, 2018, Brad Heavner, Policy Director for the California Solar & Storage Association (CALSSA), met with Maria Sotero and Adenike Adeyeye, advisors to Cmmr. Guzman Aceves, in San Francisco. Also present were Laura Gray, Energy Storage Policy Advisor for CALSSA, Josh Weiner, Director of Energy Storage Integration for NEXTracker, Asal Esfahani and Mary Claire Evans, Regulatory Analysts, Customer Generation; and John Berdner, Policy Vice President for Enphase Energy participated by the telephone. CALSSA representatives discussed DC coupled solar plus storage over 10kW within the NEM tariff as well as advice letters AL 3199-E, AL 3761-E and AL 5245-E relating to revisions to tariff schedules for customers with Virtual Net Energy Metering generation paired with a storage system in compliance with Decision 17-12-005. CALSSA representatives discussed its Petition for Modification of D.14-05-033 that argues for allowing DC-coupled solar plus storage systems that adhere to the NEM tariff. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.

b025005384f6c45099c5073e27bfc3be.description: SUMMARY:  On April 5, 2018, Pradeep Gupta, South San Francisco Councilmember and Member of Peninsula Clean Energy’s Board of Directors and Joseph F. Wiedman, Director of Legislative and Regulatory Affairs, Peninsula Clean Energy Authority (PCE), attended an ex parte meeting with Nidhi Thakar, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, in San Francisco. PCE discussed its support for the Alternate Decision and the changes it believes are necessary to support Community Choice Aggregators (CCAs) adopting disadvantaged communities (DAC)-Green Tariffs and/or community solar programs. With respect to the DAC-Green Tariff program, Mr. Wiedman pointed out that CCAs cannot access the funds identified in the Alternate Decision to support such programs. With respect to the Community Solar program, Mr. Wiedman recommended that CCAs be permitted to develop community solar programs aimed at serving their DACs regardless of whether those communities fall into the top 5% of communities per CalEnviroScreen. Mr. Wiedman stated PCE’s support for allowing a community solar facility located in one DAC to be permitted to serve customers within any DAC in a county, and the need for flexibility in timing for identifying benefiting accounts. Mr. Wiedman expressed PCE’s support for workforce development and training requirements. Mr. Gupta noted PCE’s desire to provide opportunities for residents of DACs to access renewable energy resources located in their communities.

135293ec90aafd95f8be131427728d8a.filed_by: california environmental justice alliance,Sustainable Economies Law Center
135293ec90aafd95f8be131427728d8a.description: SUMMARY:  On April 5, 2018, Shana Lazerow and Amee Raval, on behalf of California Environmental Justice Alliance (CEJA), and Subin DeVar, on behalf of Sustainable Economies Law Center (SELC), had a telephone conversation with Joanna Gubman, advisor to Cmmr. Randolph, and met with Yuliya Shmidt, advisor to Cmmr. Rechtschaffen, and Shanon O’Rourke, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in San Francisco. Ms. Lazerow expressed the parties’ support for the Alternate Proposed Decision (APD). Ms. Lazerow explained that community solar is the most similar to standard Net Energy Metering (NEM). Ms. Raval then explained that, while the parties also support Green Tariff and SASH alternatives, the Green Tariff as designed in the APD is not adequate to meet requirements as an alternative to NEM. Mr. DeVar then explained that Community Solar is legal – the legality argument, raised for the first time in a reply comment, is not well-founded in law. Ms. Lazerow explained that communities are already asking for, and contemplating, Community Solar projects that would qualify under the APD.

6d24be1a7cb6f5e6f1df1947754725a6.description: SUMMARY:  On April 5, 2018, Dan Buch, Supervisor, the Office of Ratepayer Advocates (ORA), met with Yuliya Shmidt, advisor to Cmmr. Rechtschaffen, in San Francisco. Also present were Elizabeth Fox, Public Utilities Regulatory Analyst, and Christa Salo, Staff Attorney, for the ORA. ORA representatives discussed Proposed Decision Adopting Alternatives to Promote Solar Distributed Generation in Disadvantaged Communities (PD) and Alternate PD Adopting Alternatives to Promote Solar Distributed Generation. ORA expressed its support for the DAC-Green Tariff program as the best mechanism to provide the benefits of a solar program to low-income customers in disadvantaged communities. ORA noted that the Disadvantaged Communities-Green Tariff (DAC-Green Tariff) program would be less expensive compared to the Community Solar program proposed in the APD and more efficient since the benefits of the program are narrowly tailored to low-income customers. ORA also stated that the DAC-Green Tariff program would be easy to sign up for making it likely to have a robust level of customer participation. ORA also discussed other alternatives to adopting the Community Solar program proposed in the APD.

837d6f6d096b7d01b7484fc250d2e576.description: SUMMARY:  On April 2, 2018, Dan Buch, Supervisor, the Office of Ratepayer Advocates (ORA), met with Maria Sotero, advisor to Cmmr. Guzman Aceves, in San Francisco. Also present were Elizabeth Fox, Public Utilities Regulatory Analyst, and Selina Shek, Staff Attorney, for the ORA. ORA representatives discussed the proposed Decision Adopting Alternatives to Promote Solar Distributed Generation in Disadvantaged Communities (PD) and Alternate Decision Adopting Alternatives to Promote Solar Distributed Generation in Disadvantaged Communities (APD). ORA expressed its support for the Disadvantaged Communities-Single-family Affordable Solar Housing (DAC-SASH) and DAC-Green Tariff programs with some adjustments, including adoption of the funding mechanism proposed in the APD and a minimum total bill savings threshold for low-income customers enrolling in the DAC-Green Tariff program. ORA expressed concern with adopting the Community Solar program proposed in the APD. ORA also explained its concern that the APD would waive the application of mandatory time of use (TOU) rates for DAC-SASH customers. ORA stated that if a goal of the Commission is to foster a closer community tie to and control over a shared solar generation system, the Commission could consider piloting a feed-in tariff that targeted communities can access.

McKenzie are the Presiding Officers for this proceeding. Ex parte communications are subject to Public Utilities Code Section 1701.3(h) and Article 8 of the Commission’s Rules of Practice and Procedure.

9e6283e1b0a75ac1a051564f53a41321.description: SUMMARY:  On March 27, 2018, Matthew Freedman, staff attorney for The Utility Reform Network (TURN), met with Nidhi Thakar, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, in San Francisco. TURN offered support for assistance to Disadvantaged Communities through aggressive initiatives that are narrowly tailored to serve intended beneficiaries, limit unnecessary cost shifting, are designed to succeed, and can be scaled to serve larger populations. TURN explained that these principles would be satisfied by the Proposed Decision (PD) of Administrative Law Judges Kao, McKenzie and Hecht Adopting Alternatives to Promote Solar Distributed Generation in Disadvantaged Communities. By contrast, TURN noted that the Virtual Net Energy Metering (VNEM) proposal in the Alternative PD of Cmmr. Guzman Aceves is fraught with problems that make the proposal unworkable, unreasonable, expensive, and likely to provide only a small portion of total economic benefits to low-income customers. TURN urged the Commission to defer any consideration of VNEM until future revisions to Net Energy Metering tariffs establish a uniform approach to valuing grid exports from Distributed Energy Resources.

Peterman, in San Francisco. Also present were Julia Zuckerman of NRG Energy and Rachel Bird of Borrego Energy, SEIA member companies. 933cc9e278fa163819003a71b44c9144.description: SUMMARY:  On March 14, 2018, Sidney Dietz, Director, Regulatory Relations, Pacific Gas and Electric Company (PG&E), met with Shannon O’Rourke, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in San Francisco, and had a telephonic conference with Joanna Gubman, advisor to Cmmr. Randolph; and on March 16, 2018, met with Nidhi Thakar, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, in San Francisco. Robert Kenney, Vice President, Regulatory Affairs, and Patrick Hennigan, Senior Strategic Analyst, Strategy and Policy Design, for PG&E, participated in both communications on March 14, 2018, and Patrick Hennigan also was present at the meeting of March 16, 2018. Mr. Kenney stated that the Proposed Decision (PD) is correct to focus on the low-income customer segment. Mr. Kenney further stated that the PG&E’s Disadvantaged Community (DAC) Green Tariff serves the goals of AB327 most efficiently, while the APD’s VNEM proposal is less cost-effective, and lacks customer protection. Mr. Hennigan stated that the 1.3% difference in solar NEM uptake between DACs and non-DACs can be explained by the higher proportion of low-income customers in DACs. Mr. Hennigan described PG&E’s DAC Green Tariff program and the expanded VNEM, which would allow customers to use IOU’s T&D for free. Mr. Dietz stated that PG&E’s program will also install solar in DAC communities, but without subsidies to customers who do not need it. Mr. Dietz further stated that the expansions of VNEM contemplated in the APD would simply increase the size of the program without improving its efficiency at delivering benefits to low-income customers. Written material (attached to the notice) was used in all three communications.

0877b041a0dbee32a822a4b7dc463b53.description: SUMMARY:  On March 9, 2018, Sidney Dietz, Director, Regulatory Relations, Pacific Gas and Electric Company (PG&E), met with Yuliya Shmidt, advisor to Cmmr. Rechtschaffen, in San Francisco, and on March 14, 2018, sent an electronic mail (attached to the notice) to Joanna Gubman, advisor to Cmmr.  Randolph. At the meeting with Yuliya Shmidt also present were Robert Kenney, Vice President, Regulatory Affairs, and Patrick Hennigan, Senior Strategic Analyst, Strategy and Policy Design, for PG&E. Mr. Kenney stated that the Proposed Decision is correct to focus on the low-income customer segment. Mr. Kenney further stated that the PG&E’s DAC Green Tariff serves the goals of AB327 most efficiently, while the Alternative Proposed Decision’s VNEM proposal is less cost-effective, and lacks customer protection. Mr. Hennigan stated that the 1.3% difference in solar NEM uptake between DACs and non-DACs can be explained by the higher proportion of low-income customers in DACs. Mr. Hennigan described PG&E’s DAC Green Tariff program and the expanded VNEM. Mr. Dietz stated that PG&E’s program will also install solar in DAC communities, but without subsidies to customers who do not need it. Mr. Dietz further stated that the expansions of VNEM contemplated in the APD would simply increase the size of the program without improving its efficiency at delivering benefits to low-income customers. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.

10aa8fbbe856ee8f70dd922a57fb4d7e.description: SUMMARY:  On January 10, 2018, Elise Torres, staff attorney for The Utility Reform Network (TURN), met with Maria Sotero, advisor to Cmmr. Guzman Aceves, in San Francisco. Also present were David Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Guzman Aceves, and Matthew Freedman, staff attorney with TURN. Ms. Torres discussed TURN’s recommendations for the Net Energy Metering Disadvantaged Communities alternatives and how TURN’s proposals can address barriers to solar adoption for low-income customers living in disadvantaged communities. Mr. Freedman discussed the potential for significant cost shifting and unintended consequences under some parties’ virtual net energy metering proposals. A written material (attached to this notice) was used.

b8f3759ff7c441b33814eda71fd2c8cd.description: SUMMARY:  [LATE FILED.] On December 9, 2018, Stan Greschner, Vice-President of Government Relations and Market Development of GRID Alternatives (GRID), met with David Gamson, advisor to Cmmr. Guzman Aceves, in San Francisco. Also present was Cathleen Monahan, Senior Programs Director for the GRID. GRID personnel shared their objectives for alternatives to the net energy metering (NEM) successor tariff for disadvantaged communities (DACs) being considered in this proceeding, including developing a suite of programs serving various housing arrangements, and implementing programs that will be scalable, have a high likelihood of success, and build upon ratepayer investments to the extent possible. GRID personnel explored various funding mechanisms for a Single-family Affordable Solar Homes (SASH) program augmentation. Stan Greschner urged the Commission to consider a timeline of extension/augmentation through 2030. Cathleen Monahan recommended that the Commission consider a broad definition of DACs, one that includes environmentally and economically disadvantaged communities, and is grounded in existing definitions used in Commission-led programming for the Investor-Owned Utility territories. GRID personnel described the need for ironclad consumer protection measures for low-income participants in all Commission-developed programs. GRID discussed consumer protection measures, qualifying requirements, and job training examples from the SASH program.

The meeting was hosted by the Emerson collective and the subject was “Climate, Equity and Opportunity: Onward to Implementation.” Also present were approximately 40 persons interested in clean energy access in disadvantaged communities. Mr. Wiedman noted that the Commission is currently considering utilizing virtual net metering as a means to increase access to renewable energy resources in disadvantaged communities in R.14-02-007. Mr. Wiedman stated that PCE supported utilizing virtual net metering to serve disadvantaged communities instead of only subsidizing Pacific Gas and Electric Company’s Green Tariff Shared Renewables program and encouraged the Commission to move quickly on a decision.

217571e0d28804e3a73ddd64f7edcc77.description: SUMMARY:  On November 17, 2017, Joseph Wiedman, Director of Regulatory and Legislative Affairs, Peninsula Clean Energy Authority (PCE), met with Maria Sotero, advisor to Cmmr. Guzman Aceves, in San Francisco. Mr. Wiedman discussed PCE's interest in serving customers in disadvantaged communities via innovative program offerings that utilize virtual net metering (VNM) instead of a subsidized Green Tariff Shared Renewables (GTSR)-like program. Mr. Wiedman highlighted that the cross subsidy arguments raised by parties are not based on any Commission approved methodology and that piloting a GTSR-like program and a VNM program are not mutually exclusive options. Moreover, Mr. Wiedman discussed how community choice aggregator management of a VNM-based program could address many of the other criticisms of VNM raised by proponents of subsidized GTSR-like offerings.

91e703c2523825c659d9ea33b584fdb9.description: SUMMARY:  On November 7, 2017, Sidney Dietz, Director, Regulatory Relations, Pacific Gas and Electric Company (PG&E), met with with Maria Sotero, advisor to Cmmr. Guzman Aceves, in San Francisco. Also present was Patrick Hennigan, Senior Analyst, Strategic Analytics, PG&E. Mr. Dietz stated that the strength of PG&E’s proposal, Solar CARE Plus, is that it is targeted to low-income customers, and is designed to be easy for participants compared to more project-based proposals. Mr. Hennigan described PG&E’s proposal, and noted that it is aimed entirely at low income and more of its costs go to benefits for low-income customers, unlike DAC VNEM, which would, as a net effect, put more costs onto CARE customers than it would relieve. Mr. Hennigan further stated that the Solar Care Plus projects can be directed to particular communities that have high participation and so will include the benefits within the community. Mr. Dietz stated that this low-income approach is a better approach, since it alleviates inequity more for every dollar money spent on the program, and can be scaled by the commission to appropriate levels.

0876b616f06faa4f4ca1af562ff7bde0.description: SUMMARY:  On June 28th through 30th, 2017, Cyndee Fang, Manager of Customer Pricing for San Diego Gas and Electric Company gave presentations at the Center for Research in Regulated Industries: Advanced Workshop in Regulation and Competition – 30th Annual Western Conference held in Monterey, California.  Scott Murtishaw, advisor to President Picker, was an attendee to the conference and has access to the presentations.  Fang presented the following presentation by Ken Schiermeyer & Will Matsuoka, Forecasting Long-Term Hourly Loads, and a presentation, Solar Adoption & Customer Consumption in the Residential Sector.  Fang stated that Solar Adoption and Customer Consumption presentations showed that upon further examination of the impacts to customers’ load before and after solar continues to indicate that solar adoption is unlikely to result in a reduction in the costs to serve residential solar customers.  Fang noted that while net consumption decreased one year after solar installation, over 43% increased consumption one year after installation, and on average, customers with decreased consumption in Year 1 increased consumption in Year 2, resulting in overall consumption of solar customers increasing two years after installation.  Fang explained that energy usage is not the key indicator to cost of service.  Fang noted that residential customers with solar continue to have peak levels that are over 70% higher than those without solar.  Fang indicated that average size of solar installed has increased by 51% over a 10-year period, while net consumption has increased from '250 kWh per month in 2015 to '280 kWh per month in 2016.  Written materials (attached to the notice) were used.

7e040ed849aed58c38f5d99f2738a914.description: SUMMARY:  On May 3, 2017, Scott Sarem; Co-Founder and CEO of Everyday Energy, met with Joanna Gubman, advisor to Cmmr. Martha Guzman Aceves, in San Francisco.  Also present were Kyra Bush Sarem, Co-Founder and General Counsel of Everyday Energy; Dawn Anaiscourt, Director, CPUC Regulatory Affairs, Southern California Edison Company; Sidney Dietz, Director, Regulatory Relations, and Patrick Hennigan, Senior Strategic Analyst, for Pacific Gas and Electric; Sylvia Martinez, Senior Project Manager, Community Housing Works; G Andrew Blauvelt, Coordinator, the MASH Coalition; Brad Heaver, Policy Director, California Solar Energy Industries Association (CALSEIA), and Tony Brunello from California Strategies.  The purpose of the meeting was to demonstrate that the meeting participants, who collectively have the most extensive experience in delivering solar PV to multifamily affordable housing in the state of California and have been the main participants in the Multifamily Affordable Solar Housing Program (MASH), hereinafter referred to as “the Experienced Parties” – expressed their collective agreement that the legislative intent of AB 693 is to utilize the current MASH Program infrastructure to implement AB 693, and that there is a statutory mandate for the Multifamily Affordable Housing Solar Roofs Program (MASHR) be implemented by June 30, 2017.  The Experienced Parties also discussed their concern that creating a complicated administration regime for the MAHSR Program will drive up the soft costs of providing solar and result in higher solar prices.  The Experienced Parties agree that the Commission should not fund batteries with MAHSR Program funds.  Representatives of Everyday Energy, the MASH Coalition, and CALSEIA suggested that there should be an exemption from mandatory Time of Use rates for residents of multifamily affordable housing served through virtual net metering.

7a98947710b1ded734f41f241d57845c.description: Everyday Energy noticed an oral ex-parte communication that occurred on July 7, 2016, at the Commission offices at 505 Van Ness Street in San Francisco California. The meeting began at 1:10 pm and lasted approximately 10 minutes. Scott Sarem, Co- Founder and CEO for Everyday Energy, Steve Larsen from California Strategies, Francesca Wahl, Deputy Director, Policy and Electricity Markets for SolarCity, and Scott Peattie, Senior Project Manager for SolarCity met with Scott Murtishaw, Energy Advisor in the Office of President, Michael Picker. The meeting was initiated by Mr. Sarem.  This notice is a follow up to Energy Division Staff’s request that Everyday Energy provide a more specific description of the ex parte meeting than provided in its original notice filed on Monday July 11, 2016.  Participants reviewed the legislative history of AB 693 to demonstrate the intent to provide continuity with the MASH program, clarify eligibility requirements, and ensure a primary and direct tenant benefit to low-income residents. We also discussed the timing of the proceeding in light of the recent state budget as it relates to the CPUC.

9d532825a3f1181128149b4feafd1cfb.description: Interstate Renewable Energy Council, Inc. (IREC) noticed a written ex parte communications that occurred on May 17, 2016.  The ex parte communications was in a form of a letter sent via email and U.S. Mail to Commissioner Sandoval, with copies to President Picker, Commissioner Florio, Commissioner Peterman, and Commissioner Randolph.  The letter was also signed by Brightline Defense Project, California Environmental Justice Alliance, California Solar Energy Industries Association, Everyday Energy, Sierra Club, Solar Energy Industries Association, The Alliance for Solar Choice, and Vote Solar.The parties request that Commissioner Sandoval find that IREC’s “CleanCARE” pilot program proposal is legally permissible under California law in her decision in consolidated docket Application 14-11-007 et al. The parties support the resolution of this threshold legal issue so that CleanCARE may continue to be considered and refined in R.14-07-002.

Picker, joined by telephone.  Also present were Sara Kamins and Elizabeth Curran of the Energy Division; and Dan Halperin, Director, Distributed Generation, and David Gabbard, Director, Electric Generation Interconnection, for PG&E.  Halperin stated that the queue of projects that would be eligible for NEM 1, under the joint CALSEIA/SEIA/PG&E proposal for new eligibility criteria, is now large enough to surpass the NEM 1 cap.  Halperin further stated that if the decision were made now and the cap were filled in this way, no further projects would be eligible for NEM 1, including projects that could have been eligible under the old rules. Gabbard stated that there might not be a NEM 2 tariff or an interim tariff in place. Dietz stated that some customers, with both large and small projects, have an expectation that there will be a reservation system, but that others do not have that expectation. 3a0e7ac905f9c06ca46266d3f8962bb5.description: SUMMARY:  On April 19, 2016 Sidney Dietz, Director, Regulatory Relations  Pacific Gas and Electric Company (PG&E), had a telephone communication with Nicolas Chaset, advisor to Cmmr. Picker. Dietz stated that the queue of projects that would be eligible for NEM 1, under the joint CALSEIA/SEIA/PG&E proposal for new eligibility criteria, is now large enough to surpass the NEM 1 cap. Dietz stated that if the decision were made in late May 2016, and the cap were filled with projects under the new eligibility criteria, no further projects would be eligible for NEM 1.  Dietz explained that this would, unfortunately, disadvantage a group of customers. Dietz stated that, in addition, there might not be a NEM 2 tariff or an interim tariff in place. Dietz further stated that some customers, with both large and small projects, have an expectation that there will be a reservation system, but that others do not have that expectation. Dietz further stated that other remedies, including ‘date certain’ approaches, would also not satisfy the expectations of all customers.

1d91a3f5f262dac1593523a7e8699299.description: SUMMARY: On April 7, 2016, Brad Heavner, Policy Director, California Solar Energy Industries Association (CALSEIA) spoke by phone with Scott Murtishaw, advisor to Cmmr. Picker.  Heavner stated that CALSEIA is still very much in support of the Commission issuing a decision to create a reservation system for remaining capacity in the current net energy metering tariff for Pacific Gas and Electric Company.

ffca93c1f803baf158bcd92a5726d801.description: JOINT;  SUMMARY:  On April 5, 2016, Brad Heavner, Policy Director, California Solar Energy Industries Association (CALSEIA), met with Scott Murtishaw, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, in San Francisco.  Also present were Sara Kamins of the Energy Division; Stephen Rogers, Commercial Solar Consultant of the Solar Company; and Dan Halperin, Director, Distributed Generation, David Gabbard, Director, Electric Generation Interconnection, and Sidney Dietz, Director, Regulatory Relations, for Pacific Gas and Electric Company (PG&E). Halperin described that the queue of projects that would be eligible for NEM 1, under the joint CALSEIA/SEIA/PG&E proposal for new eligibility criteria, will soon be large enough to fill up the NEM 1 cap. Halperin presented a revised version of the NEM Program Limit Report.  Dietz stated that if the cap were filled in this way, it would disadvantage a group of customers who had planned on the current eligibility rules being in place until the cap was hit. Gabbard described that because the change in eligibility would be happening late, there would be a potential gap between when NEM 1 is filled and when NEM 2 is available.  CALSEIA and PG&E representatives discussed potential for an interim tariff that could also be delayed if it is protested. Gabbard further stated that even if the decision were issued quickly, the changes in tariffs and system changes would make the proposal queue even longer if developers of solar systems for residential customers submit Customer Authorizations for projects that have been contracted but not built. Heavner described that PG&E reports its queue differently than Southern California Edison, and that PG&E has recently disclosed that there are more than 300 MW of projects under development that were not previously reported. Gabbard explained that PG&E’s NEM Program Limit Report was consistent with guidelines provided by the CPUC.   Heavner further stated that many large commercial customers have signed solar contracts with expectations of interconnecting under NEM 1, with protection from unanticipated delays through use of a reservation system. Rogers explained that delays in the interconnection study process often lead to delays in project completion. Heavner and Gabbard described a wide range of possible remedies, and stated that none would satisfy the expectations of all types of customers.  Written materials (attached to the notice) were used.

Picker, and Sean Simon, advisor to Cmmr. Randolph, in two separate meetings in San Francisco. Greenlining discussed generally its observation that the CalEnviroScreen tool is being used more frequently to define the term “disadvantaged communities,” and discussed the advantages and potential drawbacks of its use in different contexts. Relating to the second phase of this proceeding, Greenlining stated that the Commission should strive to promote greater equity and inclusion in California’s solar PV market. Greenlining discussed its preference for a broader definition of “disadvantaged communities” in the context of this proceeding.

Trimming and Shana Lazerow for California Environmental Justice Alliance (CEJA);  Ann Gressani for CHPC; Dilini Lankachandra and Eddie Ahn for Brightline; Cathleen Monahan for GRID Alternatives.  Strella Cervas for CEJA participated by telephone. Parties’ representatives described the unique requirements of AB 693 and its differences with other issues in the current NEM proceeding. 58696d896b1178351166591bf29c6a23.description: SUMMARY:  On February 29, 2016, Stephanie Chen of the Greenlining Institute (Greenlining) met with Ehren Seybert, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman San Francisco.  Also present was Joel Espino of the Greenlining.  Greenlining discussed generally its observation that the CalEnviroScreen tool is being used more frequently to define the term “disadvantaged communities,” and discussed the advantages and potential drawbacks of its use in different contexts. Relating to the second phase of this proceeding, which focuses on alternatives for disadvantaged communities, Greenlining stated that the Commission should strive to promote greater equity and inclusion in California’s solar PV market. Greenlining discussed its preference for a broader definition of “disadvantaged communities” in the context of this proceeding.

193d8037c81464f98069d86183c8f9a6.description: SUMMARY: On February 23, 2016, Stephanie Chen, representative of the Greenlining Institute (Greenlining), met with Jessica Hecht, advisor to Cmmr. Florio, in San Francisco. Also present was Joel Espino, Greenlining.  Greenlining representatives asserted that the second phase of this proceeding, focusing on alternatives for disadvantaged communities, should strive to promote greater equity and inclusion in California's solar PV market. Greenlining discussed its preference for a broader definition of "disadvantaged communities" for the upcoming phase of this proceeding focusing on alternatives for disadvantaged communities. Greenlining noted that it is appropriate to use a CalEnviroScreen-exclusive definition of disadvantaged communities (pursuant to Senate Bill 535) for programs or incentives that are closely tied to climate investments, but there are sound policy justifications supporting a broader definition for programs or incentives not directly related to climate investments.

6cf3ad64d59ec2934877064e894d0da8.description: LLC (Foundation), held a telephone conference with Nick Chaset, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, and later sent the e-mail with attachment to Nick Chaset. Matt Wilson, Chief Executive Officer of Foundation, also participated in the conference. Foundation’s representatives expressed support for the Proposed Decision (PD) in general and highlighted the areas of concern about the PD. Specifically, Foundation explained how the PD’s imposition of a new method for calculating nonbypassable charges (NBCs) would disproportionately impose charges on large commercial and industrial (LC&I) NEM customers and the impact those charges would have on the ability for the sector to sustainably grow. Foundation also discussed how LC&I customers currently pay demand charges and energy on TOU rates and that parties generally agree that LC&I customers do not contribute to any unwarranted cost shift to non-NEM customers. Foundation urged that the risk of stalling growth in the on-site wind sector combined with the absence of a cost shift problem involving LC&I NEM customers warranted exempting these customers from any changes in the methodology for calculating NBCs. Foundation offered to provide proposed modifications to the PD, which Sherr sent to Nick Chaset.  A copy of the written communication is attached to the notice.

c643a7ef3a3da262ee15f85127f3ccbb.description: [JOINT] SUMMARY:  On January 13, 2016, Joseph Wiedman, counsel for The Alliance for Solar Choice (TASC), met with Nick Chaset, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, Rachel Peterson, advisor to Cmmr. Randolph, and Ehern Seybert, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in three separate meetings in San Francisco.  At the meeting with Peterson also present was Sean Simon, advisor to Cmmr. Randolph. Lyndon Rive, Chief Executive Officer of SolarCity Corp.; Blair Swezey, California Policy Director for Sunpower, Inc.; Walker Wright, Director of Public Policy for Sunrun, Inc.; and Brandon Smithwood, Manager of California State Affairs for the Solar Energy Industries Association (SEIA), participated in all three meetings. Sanjay Ranchod, Vice President of Policy & Electricity Markets and Regulatory Counsel for SolarCity Corp., participated in the meetings with Rachel Peterson and with Ehern Seybert.  Brad Heavner, Policy Director for the California Solar Energy Industries Association (CALSEIA) participated in the meeting with Rachel Peterson.  Jeanine Cotter, CEO of Luminalt, Inc., participated in the meeting with Ehern Seybert. During these meetings, parties’ (collectively, Joint Solar Parties or JSP) representatives discussed concerns with the investor-owned utilities’ untimely proposal for a net feed-in tariff (net FiT). JSP explained that in addition to consideration of the utilities’ untimely proposal for a net FiT being barred by Commission rules of practice, a FiT would devastate sustained growth in customer-sited distributed generation because FiTs may not be financeable, result in income tax consequences for customers, and jeopardize eligibility for the federal investment tax credit. JSP noted that FiTs have been unsuccessful in supporting sustained growth of customer-sited distributed generation (DG). JSP expressed support for the Proposed Decision’s (PD) determination that time-of-use rates should be a central part of the successor tariff. JSP discussed the importance of the PD’s determination to provide 20 year grandfathering of the successor tariff.  Written materials (attached to the notice) were used.

b1ec55be2b207a40c040d65278a16462.description: SUMMARY: On January 8, 2016, Sanjay Ranchod, Vice President, Policy & Electricity Markets and Regulatory Counsel for SolarCity Corporation, met with Cmmr. Picker in Sacramento.  Nick Chaset, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, participated via videoconference.  Also present was Walker Wright, Director of Public Policy for Sunrun Inc. Ranchod and Wright discussed the mandatory time-of-use (TOU) rates aspect of the successor tariff in the Proposed Decision (PD) issued on December 15, 2015. Ranchod and Wright explained the transitional issue with imposing mandatory TOU rates in the manner and timeline described in the PD will be larger than those modeled, and recommended the Commission revise the PD to first implement default TOU rates before mandatory TOU rates. Ranchod and Wright also discussed the impact of the recent decision on net metering by the Nevada Public Utilities Commission on the rooftop solar industry in Nevada. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.

20e5210c0b57395c66258e9551ea8d69.description: SUMMARY:  On December 21, 2015, Brad Heavner, Policy Director of the California Solar Energy Industries Association (CALSEIA), met with Ehren Seybert, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, and Sean Simon, advisor to Cmmr. Randolph, in two separate meetings in San Francisco. Also present were Barry Cinnamon, President of Cinnamon Solar; Andy Schwartz, Director of Policy & Electricity Markets pf SolarCity; Walker Wright, Director of Public Policy of SunRun; and Brandon Smithwood, Manager of California State Affairs, and Tom Beach, consultant, for the Solar Energy Industries Association.  Solar representatives discussed the Proposed Decision (PD). Solar representatives expressed that effectively starting mandatory time of use rates at the beginning of the successor tariff could create customer backlash and impact customer adoption, that mandating time of use rates for net metered customers who installed solar under tiered rates would be confusing and unfair to customers, that non-bypassable charges assessed on exported power should be more limited than those listed in the PD, and that the PD would benefit from a finding that the costs of the successor tariff are approximately equal to the benefits.

2c83729fa3131afa406f1cc87a3adf9f.description: SUMMARY:  On December 21, 2015, Brad Heavner, Policy Director, California Solar Energy Industries Association (CALSEIA), met with Ehren Seybert, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, and Sean Simon, advisor to Cmmr. Randolph, in two separate meetings in San Francisco.  Also present were Barry Cinnamon, President of Cinnamon Solar; Andy Schwartz, Director of Policy & Electricity Markets for SolarCity; Walker Wright, Director of Public Policy for SunRun; and Brandon Smithwood, Manager of California State Affairs, and Tom Beach, consultant, for Solar Energy Industries Association. Solar representatives discussed the Proposed Decision (PD) in this proceeding. Solarrepresentatives expressed that effectively starting mandatory time of use rates at the beginning of the successor tariff could create customer backlash and impact customer adoption, that mandating time of use rates for net metered customers who installed solar under tiered rates would be confusing and unfair to customers, that non-bypassable charges assessed on exported power should be more limited than indicated in the PD, and that greater emphasis should be placed on the total resource cost test and societal cost test.

ffc80b604a346b2e73891fac7f69f636.description: SUMMARY:  On December 18, 2015, Dan Halperin, Director, Distributed Generation, Pacific Gas and Electric Company (PG&E), met with Ehren Seybert, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in San Francisco.  Also present were Aaron Johnson, Vice President, Customer Energy Solutions, and Erik Jacobson, Director, Regulatory Relations, for PG&E.  Halperin expressed PG&E's disappointment and opposition to the Net Energy Metering (NEM) proposed decision which does not meaningfully reduce the cost-shift in the current NEM program. Halperin stated that the proposed decision will lock in $2.5-$5.0 billion of annual cost-shifting by 2020. Johnson, Halperin and Jacobson said that the decision by Congress to extend the Investment Tax Credit (ITC) eliminates market uncertainty and will further ensure robust growth of rooftop solar. PG&E representatives said the Commission should reconsider the proposed decision in light of the ITC extension.  PG&E representatives urged the Commission to adopt a successor tariff that significantly reduces the size of this cost-shift and also results in vigorous growth of rooftop solar. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.

8c600690d46c84911a93a157f372cfd6.description: SUMMARY:  On December 21, 2015, Brad Heavner, Policy Director of the California Solar Energy Industries Association, met with Scott Murtishaw, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, in San Francisco.  Also present were: Sanjay Ranchod, Vice President of Policy and Electricity Markets for SolarCity; Walker Wright, Director of Public Policy for SunRun; and Brandon Smithwood, Manager of California State Affairs, and Tom Beach, consultant, for Solar Energy Industries Association.  Solar representatives discussed the proposed decision (PD).  Solar representatives expressed that starting mandatory time of use rates at the beginning of the successor tariff could create major customer backlash, that mandating time of use rates for net metered customers who installed solar under tiered rates would be unfair, that the list of non-bypassable charges assessed on exported power should be more limited than the list in the PD, that the new non-bypassable charges should be calculated as a fee rather than embedded in rates, and that greater emphasis should be placed on the total recourse cost test.

7ccb01382c2c543dbd015af69172e218.description: Amended Scoping Memo and Ruling of Assigned Commissioner.  Rulemaking 14-07-002 is categorized as ratesetting. Hearing is determined to be needed. The amended scope of issues and schedule are as set forth. The duration of this proceeding is 18 months from the date of this scoping memo and ruling. Rule 8.2(c) and Rule 8.3 apply with respect to ex parte communications. Commissioner Michael Picker is the assigned Commissioner. Administrative Law Judge Anne E. Simon is the presiding officer for this proceeding.

b0de668745f8daa03ec5e0109ef76006.description: SUMMARY:  On December 7, 2015, Dan Skopec, Vice President of Regulatory Affairs of San Diego Gas & Electric Company (SDG&E), met with Ehren Seybert, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, Sean Simon, advisor to Cmmr. Randolph, and Scott Murtishaw, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, in three separate meetings in San Francisco.  Also present were Brian Prusnek, Director of Regulatory Affairs, and Cyndee Fang, Manager of Rates, for SDG&E. Skopec provided an update to the growing cost-shift that is being imposed on non-participating customers of SDG&E. Prusnek described the importance of eliminating the retail rate netting. Fang described multiple scenarios using the Public Tool. Written materials (attached to the notice) were used.

b407737cf69a6be342c8fbb4d34284c9.description: SUMMARY:  On December 3, 2015, Steve Malnight, Senior Vice President, Regulatory Affairs, Pacific Gas and Electric Company (PG&E), met with Nick Chaset, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, in San Francisco.  Also present were Dan Halperin, Director, Distributed Generation, and Erik Jacobson, Director, Regulatory Relations, for PG&E. Malnight stated that PG&E’s approach to NEM reform keys off the objectives of AB 327 and ensuring there is sustainable growth of rooftop solar. Malnight described three key principles for NEM reform. Malnight challenged the assertion of solar parties that NEM reform will derail the solar industry and there is no room to lower PPA prices. Malnight also described PG&E’s concern over the large subsidy of about $2,000 per participant if the existing approach to NEM continues. Halperin explained why PG&E will continue to see rapid growth of distributed generation adoption under PG&E’s proposal. Malnight described the unreasonable avoided cost estimates advocated by the solar parties and challenged their RPS premium assumption. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.

7fee1ee500cde161edfcb5a9def9d3ac.description: SUMMARY:  On December 2, 2015, Brandon Smithwood, California State Affairs Manager for Solar Energy Industries Association (SEIA) met, on behalf of SEIA, California Solar Energy Industries Association (CALSEIA), The Alliance for Solar Choice (TASC) and Vote Solar, with Nick Chaset, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, in San Francisco.  Also present were Tom Beach, consultant for SEIA and Vote Solar, Susannah Churchill, Regional Director-West Coast for Vote Solar, Brad Heavner, Policy Director for CALSEIA, and Walker Wright, representative for TASC. The solar representatives provided clarification of the importance of net-metering in the face of a pending expiration of the federal Investment Tax Credit.  The representatives of SEIA and TASC discussed their concerns with the draft version of the Public Tool, focusing on the adoption models for solar and storage that are included in the Tool.  The SEIA and TASC representatives recommended that Energy Division and E3 modify these elements of the Tool, as they are difficult for users to know how to change. Written materials (attached to the notice) were used.

0b63484ba8ca632229de2512cc810048.description: SUMMARY:  On November 30, 2015, John Pimentel, President of Foundation Windpower, LLC (Foundation) met with Ehren Seybert, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in San Francisco.  Also present was Steve Sherr, Senior Vice President of Foundation. During the meeting, the Foundation representatives reviewed the substance of Foundation's opening and reply comments filed in the Commission's NEM Successor Tariff Proceeding, including topics such as increasing the NEM cap above 1.0 MW, interpretation of Section 2827.1(b)(5), how grid impacts are addressed under Rule 21, costs of wind energy, and barriers to sustainable growth of distributed wind under certain proposed successor tariffs. The Foundation representatives also provided examples of how wind energy technology, challenges and opportunities differ from other distributed energy resources.

014c2b7adffd83ef37813616ffe9b94b.description: SUMMARY:   On November 23, 2015, Brad Heavner, Policy Director for the California Solar Energy Industries Association (CALSEIA), met with Ehren Seybert, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in San Francisco. Also present were Rick Brown, President, TerraVerde Renewable Partners, Tom Williard, Principal, Sage Renewables, and Andrew Hoffman, Senior Director of Strategy and Development, CalCom Solar.  Parties' representatives expressed that it is essential for school customers and agricultural customers to continue to have the opportunity to stabilize their energy costs with on-site generation, and that the opportunity would be eliminated under the utility proposals for a net metering successor tariff. Parties' representatives explained the need to maintain the current distinction between distribution upgrades and interconnection facilities. Parties' representatives also expressed the goal of increasing efficiency in order to continue lowering prices and expanding the customer opportunity of installing solar power. Written materials (attached to the notice) were used.

4c190686753ce759c1f8dbde63513144.description: [Pursuant to D.14-11-041] SUMMARY: On November 13, 2015, Aaron Johnson, Vice President, Customer Energy Solutions, Pacific Gas and Electric Company (PG&E), initiated the communication with Edward Randolph, Director of the Energy Division. Also present were: Sarah Kamins, Supervisor, Customer Generation Programs, Energy Division; Sidney Dietz, Director, Regulatory Relations, PG&E; Dan Skopec, Vice President of Regulatory Affairs, and Caroline Winn, Chief Energy Delivery Officer, for San Diego Gas & Electric; Brad Heavner, Policy Director, California Solar Energy Industries Association, and Brandon Smithwood, California State Affairs Manager, Solar Energy Industries Association. Johnson stated that PG&E supports the solar-rooftop industry's efforts to provide certainty about whether a customer will be on the original or successor Net Energy Metering (NEM) tariff and about the treatment of customers during a possible 'gap' identified between PG&E hitting the NEM cap and the possibly-delayed NEM successor decision. Johnson further stated that the a reservation system could solve the uncertainty problem, but that it would cause the automated interconnection process, which takes from one to three days, to be replaced by a manual interconnection process, which would likely take thirty to forty five days.   Johnson stated that PG&E could support an interim 'gap' tariff that would mitigate uncertainty for customers who sign up after the cap. Dietz stated that either solution would require a revised NEM tariff and, if protested, could take as long or longer than the NEM successor decision and its tariff revision.

0c426d3376a9238a530370395b419384.description: SUMMARY: On November 12, 2015, Brad Heavner, Policy Director for the California Solar Energy Industries Association (CALSEIA), met with Scott Murtishaw, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, in San Francisco. Also present were Don Osborn, President of Spectrum Solar, and Jeanine Cotter, President, for Luminalt Solar.  CALSEIA representatives expressed that continuation of virtual net metering is essential to maintaining the opportunity for apartment buildings to install solar power, and that reducing export compensation would effectively make both the low income and market rate virtual net metering tariffs unusable. CALSEIA explained its proposal that the single service delivery point limitation in the current market rate VNEM tariff be eliminated to conform with the participation rules in the current low income VNEM tariff. CALSEIA representatives also stressed the need to maintain diversity in the solar industry.

b374f2e31b9e2794bc33cff431bb1cb4.description: JOINT; SUMMARY:  On Thursday November 12, 2015, Matt Klopfenstein, attorney of record for NLine Energy, met with Michele Kito, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, and Ehren Seybert, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in two separate meetings in San Francisco.  Also present were Gary Arant, Scott McClelland and Joshua Nelson, attorney of record for the Inland Empire Utilities Agency, Padre Dam Municipal Water District, Rancho California Water District, Sweetwater Authority, TerraVerde Renewable Partners and Valley Center Municipal Water District (collectively, the Net-Energy Metering Public Agency Coalition 2.0 or NEM-PAC 2.0). Nelson outlined NEM-PAC 2.0's concerns regarding ensuring that the successor tariff takes into the account the unique economics of public projects, retains net energy metering aggregation for all customers and remains economic for public agencies and non-solar technologies. McClelland provided an overview of concerns regarding the pending SDG&E cap on NEM 1.0.   Arant provided an overview of his concerns with regulatory uncertainty. Klopfenstein discussed the unique benefits of in-conduit hydro, the importance and relative size of non-residential distributed generation and the need for a reservation or similar system for projects currently in the pipeline. Written materials (attached to the notice) were used.

f74ea82cd20904e8f8b4be5fb91334ca.description: SUMMARY:  On November 12, 2015, Michael Hoover, Director of State Regulatory Affairs, Southern California Edison Company (SCE), met with Nick Chaset, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, and Ehren Seybert, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in two separate meetings in San Francisco.  Hoover provided a walk-through of the slides to explain SCE's Proposal for the successor to the Net Energy Metering tariff under Assembly Bill 327 and why it satisfied the statutory standard for mitigating the cost shift to non-participating customers while supporting the continued growth of customer-sited renewable generation in a sustainable manner. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.

9f6e2feb52425059bd0e295c55975c91.description: [Pursuant to D.14-11-041] SUMMARY:  On October 21, 2015, Aaron Johnson, Vice President of Customer Energy Solutions, Pacific Gas and Electric Company (PG&E) met with Edward Randolph, Director of the Energy Division, in San Francisco. Also present were Dan Halperin, Director, Distributed Generation, and Sidney Dietz, Director, Regulatory Relations, for PG&E.  Halperin described the growth in rooftop solar in PG&E's service territory and stated that PG&E is providing industry-leading interconnection and support for solar customers. Johnson stated that, even with the reduction of the Investment Tax Credit (ITC), rooftop solar adoption will be high. Johnson further stated that prices are already below the base case expectations reflected in the Public Tool model. Written material (attached to the notice) was used.

a4a0cd6ebe2dee5a3990de004c19e997.description: SUMMARY: On October 8, 2015, Sanjay Ranchod, Vice President of Policy & Electricity Markets and Regulatory Counsel for SolarCity Corporation, met with Sean Simon, advisor to Cmmr. Randolph, Jessica Hecht, advisor to Cmmr. Florio, and Scott Murtishaw, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, in three separate meetings in San Francisco.  Also present were Brad Heavner, Policy Director, and Brandon Smithwood, California State Affairs Manager, for the Solar Energy Industries Association; Tom Beach, Principal at Crossborder Energy; Susannah Churchill, West Coast Regional Director for Vote Solar; Walker Wright, Director of Public Policy for Sunrun, Inc.; and Blair Swezey, Director of Market Development and Public Policy at SunPower Corporation.  The parties expressed concern about the adverse impact of new fixed monthly charges or fees on the growth of the distributed solar market.  The parties also discussed how continued growth of rooftop solar depends on customer bill savings.  The parties further noted that the Office of Ratepayer Advocates' successor tariff proposal would have impacts on adoption as severe as the investor-owned utilities' proposals.  The parties discussed how Arizona's experience with new charges and fees illustrates that these policy changes can practically eliminate customer adoption of solar.  The parties distributed a handout at all three of these meetings. In the meetings with Simon and Hecht, the parties distributed six letters.  Copies of the written materials are attached to the notice.

5795d921cb5b2ac0f45cbab584c5a400.description: SUMMARY:  On September 14, 2015, at 4:00 PM, Brian Prusnek, Director of Regulatory Affairs, San Diego Gas and Electric Company (SDG&E), had a phone call with Scott Murtishaw, advisor to Cmmr. Picker. Prusnek explained that the numbers that SDG&E files monthly in compliance with D.14-03-041 are useful but do not accurately portray how close SDG&E is to the NEM cap because they include applications received which may or may not materialize. SDG&E is planning to place on its website, the actual number of customers that have been interconnected and NEM applications in the queue that SDG&E has received Final Electrical Inspection release from city/county and is waiting for authorization to operate from SDG&E, updated twice daily, so that installers can have immediate information on SDG&E's progress towards the NEM cap.

57d19e8ce96ff396f2ce92ab1599e354.description: [Joint] SUMMARY:  On May 13, 2015, R. Thomas Beach, outside consultant for the Solar Energy Industries Association (SEIA), met with Scott Murtishaw, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, in San Francisco.  Also present were Marc Kolb, Eliah Gilfenbaum, and Andy Schwartz of The Alliance for Solar Choice (TASC), and Mark Fulmer, outside consultant for TASC.  The representatives of SEIA and TASC discussed their concerns with the draft version of the Public Tool, focusing on the adoption models for solar and storage that are included in the Tool. They also discussed the structure of the cost of service model and the importance of other options to curtailment for dealing with possible renewable over-generation in a 50% RPS scenario. The SEIA and TASC representatives recommended that Energy Division and E3 modify these elements of the Tool, as they are difficult for users to know how to change.

802e90550ecb5f2ac1256ffe97ad8791.filed_by: California Association of School Business Officials
802e90550ecb5f2ac1256ffe97ad8791.description: SUMMARY:  On May 15, 2015, Jeffrey Vaca, Deputy Executive Director of the California Association of School Business Officials, sent a letter to Cmmr. Picker. Copies of the letter were also sent to Cmmrs. Carla Peterman, Florio, Sandoval and Randolph. The letter was also signed by Laura Preston, Legislative Advocate for the Association of California School Administrators, and Dennis Meyers, Assistant Executive Director for the California School Boards Association. The letter urged the Commission to continue California's current net energy metering program beyond 2017, so as to preserve the benefits of installing solar for California schools.  A copy of the letter is attached to the notice.

49344691a55ff79f75672a1b11e0d8f4.description: SUMMARY:   On November 5 and 6, 2015, Dan Skopec, Vice President of Regulatory Affairs, San Diego Gas and Electric Company (SDG&E), had two meetings in San Francisco: on November 5 - with Scott Murtishaw, advisor to Cmmr. Picker, and on November 6 - with Ehren Seybert, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman.  Also present was Brian Prusnek, Director of Regulatory Affairs, SDG&E. Skopec explained that SDG&E's proposal is the most effective in the proceeding at reducing the cost-shift that is created by participating customers on to non-participating customers under the Net Energy Metering program.  Prusnek provided a walk-through of the slides. A copy of the slides is attached to the notice.

b446b1eebf301bb2fe2fb7b97207fbc3.description: Sierra Club noticed two oral and written ex-parte communications.  The first meeting was held with Scott Murtishaw, advisor to President Picker, on October 27, 2015.  The second meeting was held with Ehren Seybert, advisor to Commissioner Peterman, on October 28, 2015.  At both meetings, Sierra Club urged the Commission to acknowledge the wider societal benefits of rooftop solar that have value for all Californians, including avoided climate impacts, better grid resiliency, and improvements to human health.

1b0c25bfa2239151b8ca03ee176c67f5.description: Center for Sustainable Energy ® (CSE) noticed an oral written ex-parte communication with Scott Murtishaw, Energy Advisor to President Michael Picker, on October 27, 2015; to emphasize that while CSE is supportive of an incremental approach to changing Net Energy Metering, do not support the specific Installed Capacity Fee rate design option that the Office of Ratepayer Advocates has proposed.

d9943c47b212824140b21a5cf916c8c2.filed_by: The Alliance for Solar Choice,Solar Energy Industries Association,California Solar Energy Industries Association,Vote Solar
d9943c47b212824140b21a5cf916c8c2.description: [Joint] SUMMARY: On October 9, 2015, Andy Schwartz, Director of Policy and Electricity Markets for SolarCity Corporation, met with Ehren Seybert, advisor to Cmmr. Peterman, in San Francisco.  Also present were Brad Heavner, Policy Director, and Brandon Smithwood, California State Affairs Manager, for the Solar Energy Industries Association; Tom Beach, Principal at Crossborder Energy; Susannah Churchill, West Coast Regional Director for Vote Solar; and Kim Sanders, Senior Manager of Public Policy for Sunrun, Inc.  The parties expressed concern about the adverse impact of new fixed monthly charges or fees on the growth of the distributed solar market.  The parties also discussed how continued growth of rooftop solar depends on customer bill savings.  The parties further noted that the Office of Ratepayer Advocates' successor tariff proposal would have impacts on adoption as severe as the investor-owned utilities' proposals.  The parties discussed how Arizona's experience with new charges and fees illustrates that these policy changes can practically eliminate customer adoption of solar.  Written materials (attached to the notice) were used.

5dcc8a8dc39f04c0aac50752478174f6.description: SUMMARY:  On September 17, 2015, Brad Heavner, Policy Director of the California Solar Energy Industries Association, sent an email to Cmmr. Picker.  The email was copied to his Nick Chaset, Ken Koss, and Scott Murtishaw, advisors to Cmmr. Picker. The email contained a letter describing emergency conditions in San Diego related to the transition to a net metering successor tariff and requesting that the Commission take action. A copy of the email and letter are attached to this notice.
